{"author":{"id":"1949ffc23f11a8cb4f8c42a45c9ad241b49570df9a18687489e9ea78d87c54a3"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1772048170,"nonce":"euMXSFteqBPeGnwTt0liHgcSYpE=","message":"[GitHub comment by i-m-mll on 2026-02-05T03:35:33Z]\n\n## Extension: Penzai subgraphs as a component type\n\nBeyond building a Penzai-*like* selector API native to Equinox, there's a complementary option: support actual Penzai models as a special subgraph type within feedbax graphs.\n\n### Motivation\n\nPenzai's value isn't just selectors — it's the integrated \"surgery-first\" workflow:\n- Treescope visualization (interactive tree inspection)\n- Named axes / slot system for explicit tensor dimension tracking  \n- Layers designed for inspectability and modification\n- REPL-style inspect-modify-inspect cycles in notebooks\n\nUsers doing interpretability research might prefer defining their neural networks in Penzai's native style, while still embedding them in feedbax's graph system for the broader model (tasks, mechanics, training infrastructure).\n\n### Proposed approach\n\n| Layer | Tool |\n|-------|------|\n| Feedbax graph + Equinox components | Feedbax-native selectors (#38 core proposal) |\n| \"Penzai subgraph\" nodes | Actual Penzai models with native selectors/visualization |\n| Bridge at boundary | Feedbax wraps/unwraps at subgraph entry/exit |\n\nThis would be similar to how we're considering DAE/acausal subgraphs (#49) for physical systems — a domain-specific subgraph type with its own conventions.\n\n### Open questions\n\n- How do Penzai's named axes interact with feedbax's port system?\n- Can Treescope visualize mixed Equinox/Penzai trees, or only at the Penzai subgraph level?\n- Is the impedance mismatch between Equinox's functional style and Penzai's surgery style manageable at the boundary?\n\n### Relationship to this issue\n\nThis is orthogonal to building native feedbax selectors:\n1. Native selectors (#38 core) — for Equinox-based feedbax components\n2. Penzai subgraphs (this extension) — for users who want Penzai's full workflow inside feedbax\n\nBoth could coexist. Treescope integration (#39) benefits either approach.\n\n---\nCo-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.5 \u003cnoreply@anthropic.com\u003e","files":null}]}